1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ {You may have noticed that I have
slightly changed the initial move order. The reason is that the system
examined in this line is based on retreating the bishop to d6.} 5. Bd2 Bd6 {
This has become fashionable lately, while in the past it was not considered
seriously.} 6. Nc3 $5 {I find this move order best. Depending on Black's move
order White could play Qc2 and e2-e4. The bishop needs staying for a while on
f1 in order to retrieve the pawn on c4 if needed. Do mind the move order after:
1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 d5 as now only 4.Nf3 allows the plan examined here.} (6.
Bg2 c6 7. O-O {is too slow. After} Nbd7 $1 8. Nc3 {can be met by} (8. b3 Ne4 $1
{and Black manages to get his desired Stonewall-setup.}) 8... dxc4 $1 {The
bishop stands badly on d2 for several reasons. White cannot react with Nd2 and
if ...e6-e5 he cannot deprive Black of the right to castle.}) {The most
flexible move order, keeping options such as ...c7-c5 and even more
importantly, ...Nc6.} 6... O-O (6... c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 {After ...c7-c6 it makes
no sense playing c4-c5 as Black could retreat with the bishop to c7
threatening ... e6-e5.} (7... dxc4 8. e4 $16) 8. e4 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4
{Having kept the bishop on f1, White can now use it for a kingside attack.} Qe7
(10... O-O 11. Bd3 Nf6 12. Qh4 $16) (10... Nf6 11. Qc2 O-O 12. Bg2 b6 13. O-O
Bb7 14. c5 Bc7 15. Rfe1 $16 {Sebenik,M (2534)-Swayams,M (2491) chess.com INT
2017 (0-1, 67)}) 11. O-O-O Nf6 12. Qc2 b6 {is the most logical, but not really
enough for equalizing.} (12... Bd7 {is too passive to be good.} 13. Bg2 (13.
Ne5 a5 14. Rg1 c5 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. d5 e5 17. f4 O-O 18. Bd3 Nf6 19. Rde1 $16 {
Kashlinskaya,A (2448)-Khademalsharieh,S (2380) Doha 2015 (0-1, 50)}) 13...
O-O-O 14. Rhe1 Kb8 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. f4 $16 {Kraemer,M (2567)-Haimovich,T (2383)
Biel 2016 (½-½, 32)}) 13. Bd3 (13. c5 $5 {[%csl Gc8]} bxc5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15.
Bb4 Bxb4 16. Qxc6+ Nd7 17. Qxa8 Qc5+ {[%csl Ga7]} 18. Kb1 O-O 19. Bd3 $14)
13... Bb7 14. Rhe1 {½-½ Paehtz, E (2489)-Atalik, E (2408) Mamaia 2016
Obviously a premature agreement to a draw:} O-O 15. Ng5 h6 16. Nh7 Nxh7 17.
Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Be4 $36 {[%cal Gf2f4] /\f2-f4.}) ({I had watched the following
game from close, during the first round of the Baku Olympiad:} 6... Nbd7 7. c5
Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O c6 10. b4 Ne4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qd4 14.
Qc2 Qxe5 15. Bxe4 f5 16. Bf3 Bf6 17. Rab1 Qc7 18. e4 $16 {Lupulescu,C (2618)
-Pace,C (2172) Baku 2016 (1-0, 31)}) (6... Nc6 $5 {is a relatively unexplored
continuation, but it seems to lead to a slightly more pleasant ending for
White.} 7. Bg5 dxc4 8. e4 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12.
O-O-O+ ({White's advantage is only symbolic after} 12. f4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 h6 14.
O-O-O+ Ke8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxc4 Be6 {Saduakassova,D (2411)-Khademalsharieh,S
(2450) Abu Dhabi 2016 (½-½, 39)}) 12... Ke8 13. Bxc4 Be6 (13... Bxc3 {
is a small concession as it increases White's control in the centre.} 14. bxc3
Be6 15. Bd5 Bxd5 {Hoang,T (2463)-Kozak,A (2361) Budapest 2017 (1-0, 44)} 16.
Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rxd5 $14 {Due to the rook's activity long the fifth rank, Both
Black's wings are vulnerable.}) 14. Bd5 c6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 {This kind of
weakness may count in several types of endings.} 16. f3 h6 17. Be3 b6 18. Ne2
Kf7 19. g4 Rad8 20. h4 c5 {Pogonina,N (2492)-Khademalsharieh,S (2435)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2016 (0-1, 60)} 21. h5 $14) 7. Bg5 $1 {Another accurate move.}
({If} 7. Bg2 {Black's best is} Nc6 {preparing ...dxc4 followed by ...e6-e5.
Since Black has castled the same plan as above does not work anymore.}) 7... c6
{With the given move order Black needs spending a tempo on this consolidating
move.} (7... Be7 8. Bg2 Nbd7 9. Qd3 $14 {actually offers White an extra tempo
over normal Catalan lines as his bishop has wasted one more tempo than White's.
And if} h6 10. Bf4 {the move ...h7-h6 is not especially useful, at least not
on short term.}) (7... dxc4 8. e4 Be7 9. Bxc4 $16) 8. Bg2 h6 ({Neutral play
based on} 8... Nbd7 {allows opening the centre:} 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Bb4+ (
10... Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Bb4 12. Nc3 e5 13. a3 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Qa6 {Meier,G (2640)
-Adams,M (2725) Baden-Baden 2013 (½-½, 35) Black hopes keeping the white
king in the centre with ...Qxc4 but White can avoid that:} 15. O-O $1 $146 Qxc4
16. dxe5 Ne4 17. Bd4 $16) 11. Nc3 $1 (11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Nexd2 {allows} e5 13.
dxe5 Re8 14. O-O Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11) 11... h6 (
11... c5 12. O-O cxd4 13. Qxd4 $14 {with better development. It ill not be
easy activating the c8-bishop.}) (11... e5 12. dxe5 Qe7 13. Qd4 Bc5 14. Qf4 Qe6
15. O-O Ng4 16. Rae1 h6 17. Bh4 g5 18. Bxg5 Nxf2 19. Rxf2 hxg5 20. Qxg5+ Qg6
21. Qd2 $16 {with a dangerous attack.}) 12. Bf4 Ne4 13. Qc2 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Ba5
15. O-O Bc7 16. Qe4 (16. Bxc7 Qxc7 17. a4 $14) 16... Bxf4 17. Qxf4 b6 18. Rfd1
Bb7 19. c5 $14 {Onischuk,A (2665)-Naroditsky,D (2633) Saint Louis 2015 (1-0,
50)}) (8... dxc4 9. Nd2 $14) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. O-O {After castling White
already plans e2-e4, without fearing a check on b4. Due to the threat e4-e5,
Black would have no time to react with ...dxc4.} Bc7 (10... Qd8 $5 {is the
other way of anticipating Wite's plan. Gledura,B (2500)-Bluebaum,M (2589)
Karpacz 2015 (0-1, 49).} 11. c5 Be7 12. e4 $14) 11. e3 $5 {A flexible move
preparing Qe2 and keeping all the possible plans.} (11. e4 dxc4 $5) 11... Nd7 (
11... dxc4 12. Nd2 e5 13. d5 $1 Rd8 14. Qe2 Bf5 15. Qxc4 Nd7 16. dxc6 (16. Nde4
Qg6 17. dxc6 Nb6 18. Qe2 bxc6 19. Rfc1 $14 {Bosiocic,M (2623)-Bolourchifard,F 
(2314) Khomeyn 2017 (1-0, 35)}) 16... bxc6 (16... Nb6 17. Nd5 $1 Rxd5 18. cxb7
Nxc4 19. bxa8=Q+ Rd8 20. Qb7 Nxd2 21. Qxc7 Nxf1 22. Rxf1 $14) 17. Nce4 Qe6 18.
Rfc1 $14) 12. Qe2 Qe7 (12... dxc4 13. Nd2 Rd8 14. Nxc4 Nb6 15. f4 Qe7 16. Ne4
Nd5 17. Rac1 Rb8 18. a3 Bd7 19. Ne5 Be8 20. Nc5 f6 21. Ned3 $14 {Bosiocic,M 
(2616)-Sunilduth Lyna,N (2564) Helsingor 2017 (½-½ 70)}) 13. Rfd1 (13. Rac1
$5 {is an interesting alternative, threatening to win a pawn on d5 and forcing
Black making some concession.} Nf6 14. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] /\f4. (Wagner)})
13... Nf6 (13... b6 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. e4 $14 {leaves the c7-bishop misplaced.})
14. e4 dxc4 (14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bd7 17. c5 $14 {Wagner}) 15. e5
{Restricting the c7-bishop and consolidating White's space advantage.} Nd5 16.
Qxc4 Rd8 17. Ne4 $14 {Gelfand,B (2751)-Ding,L (2749) Wenzhou 2015 (0-1, 75)
Black's position is solid but quite passive. White has more space and can
prepare to transfer his king's knight to c4 followed by an invasion on d6.} *

