1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 {This is the traditional
bishop retreat. In many lines, White's "extra tempo" with respect to the
normal closed lines below will actually spoil his coordination slightly, as
the bishop stands in the way of his knights and rooks.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
8. Qc2 c6 {The most solid and popular continuation, mainly preparing ...b7-b6
without being forced to play an unfavorable version of the hanging pawns after
cxd5. Now and later Black can consider transposing to a Stonewall structure
with a knight jump to e4.} (8... Ne4 9. Nc3 Nxd2 ({SInce d5 is hanging Black
is best adviced to release the tension getting the bishops' pair in exchange.} 
9... f5 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 exd5 12. c4 $16) 10. Nxd2 c6 11. Rad1 (11. e4 {
is premature.} dxe4 12. Ndxe4 (12. Bxe4 Nf6 {leaves the d4-pawn hanging.})
12... f5 13. Nd2 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Rfe1 Qc7 $11 {Predojevic,B (2642)
-Nisipeanu,L (2687) Baku 2016 (½-½, 31)}) 11... f5 12. e3 Bd6 13. a3 Qe7 14.
f4 b6 15. Nf3 Bb7 16. Ne5 Kh8 17. b4 $14 {White has neutralized Black's
kingside attacking chances and retains queenside space advantage.} a5 $6 18. b5
cxb5 19. cxd5 b4 20. dxe6 Bxg2 21. Qxg2 Nxe5 {Marin-Lupulescu, Alba Iulia 
(rapid) 2017} 22. dxe5 bxc3 23. Rxd6 b5 24. Qd5 $18) 9. Rd1 {In order to
understand White's play we must know that Black has a choice between ...Bb7
and ...Ba6. Against the former, he would develop his knight on the most active
square, c3, while against the latter he must come up with something different.
Therefore, he needs playing a few neutral but useful moves until Black will
reveal his cards.} b6 ({Once again} 9... Ne4 {is possible.} 10. Be1 {AFter the
rook's development the bishop can retreat to this safe square. The bishop is
not passive as it sustains b2-b4 and in some cases, it can go to f2 after
f2-f3. Black has two main plans now.} b5 (10... f5 11. Nbd2 Bd6 (11... a5 12.
Nb3 a4 13. Nc1 $14 {is a familiar manoeuvre.}) 12. b4 $1 Qe7 (12... Bxb4 13.
Nxe4 Bxe1 14. Neg5 $16) 13. Rab1 b5 14. c5 Bc7 15. Nb3 g5 16. Nc1 g4 17. Nh4
Qg7 18. f3 Ng5 19. Bf2 Nh3+ 20. Bxh3 gxh3 21. Kh1 a5 22. a3 Nf6 23. Nd3 Bd7 24.
Rg1 $14 {Cramling, P (2444)-Greet, A (2447) Dundee 2017 (1-0, 48) White has
stabilized the position and she only needs preparing a pawn break to get a
clear advantage.}) 11. Ne5 $1 ({Taking advantage of the hanging e4-knight.
This is one of the cases when the standard plan} 11. c5 {leaves White somewhat
passive:} a5 12. Nbd2 f5 13. Nb3 g5 14. Nc1 g4 15. Nd2 Bf6 16. e3 Qe7 17. Ne2
e5 $132 {Marin,M (2528)-Bischoff,K (2504) Porto Mannu 2017 (½-½, 42)}) 11...
Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qb6 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 $14 {Vokoun,J (2238)-Cifka,S (2370)
Prague 2007 (0-1, 36) Black does not quite have enough compensation for the
pawn and weakened structure as the bishop will not be able to create threats
against the king after a later f2-f3.}) ({If} 9... b5 {The correct reaction is}
10. c5 {already.} a5 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. e3 $1 {The most active treatment of the
position. The d2-square is left free for the knight and an exchange on f4
would just open the e-file for White.} Bb7 (12... f5 13. Nbd2 Nhf6 14. Ng5 Nb8
{Bauer,C (2602)-Fernandes,A (2415) San Sebastian 2009 (1-0, 36)} 15. h4 h6 16.
Nh3 Nbd7 17. Nf3 $14) 13. Nbd2 g5 $6 {The bishop is irritating, of course, but
this move weakens the kingside and the dark squares too much.} 14. Bd6 Bxd6 15.
cxd6 f5 16. Nb3 $16 {Markus,R (2602)-Vojinovic,G (2466) Palic 2014 (½-½, 27)}
) 10. b3 Ne4 {The last moment when we investigate this knight jump. The main
lines:} (10... Bb7 {,}) (10... Ba6 {and}) (10... a5 {are examinated separately
below.}) 11. Ne1 $1 {Since Black has weakened his queenside already, the
exchange on d2 is not a problem anymore.} (11. Bf4 Bb7 12. Nc3 f5 13. Ne5 Nxe5
14. Bxe5 Nf6 $11 {Bai,J (2518)-Yu,Y (2724) China 2015 (½-½, 43)}) 11... Nxd2
(11... f5 {loses a pawn with incomplete compensation:} 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qc6
Ba6 14. Qxe6+ Kh8 15. Qxd5 Bxe2 16. Rc1 $14) (11... Ndf6 12. Bf4 $14 {leaves
Black wthout counterplay in the centre.}) 12. Nxd2 Bb7 13. e4 $14 *

