1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 b6 10. b3 Bb7 {The most natural developing move, which, however,
allows White playing the desirable:} 11. Nc3 Ba6 $5 {Trying to out-trick White.
} ({The meutral} 11... Rc8 {allows} 12. e4 ({White should hurry with the
central break as after} 12. Bf4 c5 13. cxd5 {Black already has} cxd4 14. Nxd4
Nxd5 {with an unpleasant pin.}) 12... c5 {is the thematic reaction, but with
the knight on c3 it is not too effective.} (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 c5 {is an
attempt to take advantage of the unfavorable placement of the bishop on d2,
neutralizing the pin along the d-file.} 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Bc3 {lack faces the
threat Ng5 with unpleasant pressure on h7.} Be4 (15... Qc7 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17.
Ng5 $14 {gets the bishops' pair as} Bxg2 $2 18. Bxf6 g6 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Nxh7
Kxh7 21. Kxg2 $16 {wins a pawn, Buhmann,R (2598)-Matt,F (2248) Aschach 2012 
(1-0, 28)}) 16. Qe2 Qc7 17. dxc5 Qxc5 (17... bxc5 18. Ne5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qb7+
20. Qf3 Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 $14 {White can combine the plan based on g4-g5 with
attacking Black weak queenside pawns.}) (17... Bxc5 18. Bxf6 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 gxf6
20. Qxf6 $14) 18. Bxf6 Bxf3 19. Bxe7 Bxe2 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Rd7 $16 a6 22. f3
$18 {The bishop is trapped, Wells, P (2427)-O'Donnell, C (2303) Bunratty 2016 
(½-½, 41)}) 13. exd5 exd5 14. Be3 {The central tension favors White as he is
better developed. Black mainly faces problems with finding a good square for
his queen.} dxc4 15. d5 $1 {Threatening to trap the bishop with d5-d6.} Ng4 16.
Bf4 cxb3 (16... Bf6 17. bxc4 Ba6 18. Rac1 Bxc4 19. Ne4 Ba6 20. Nd6 Ra8 21. Qf5
$16 {Grandelius,N (2562)-Firat,B (2423) Athens 2012 (1-0, 36)}) 17. axb3 $16 {
WHite has overwhelming initiative for the pawn.} c4 $5 (17... a6 18. h3 Nh6 19.
Bxh6 gxh6 20. Ra4 $16) 18. Rxa7 cxb3 19. Qxb3 $16 {Swiercz,D (2645) -Xiong,J 
(2674) Saint Louis 2017 (1-0, 27)}) 12. Bf4 {White uses the extra tempo to
activate his bishop and clear the d2-square for the knight.} Nh5 (12... Rc8 13.
e4 dxc4 14. Nd2 b5 (14... c5 15. d5 $16) 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Bf1 {This is a
typical Queen's Indian/Catalan structure, but with an extra tempo for White.
Black's extr pawn is not relevant nor safe while White has a strong centre.}
Nb6 (16... Bb4 {Kreisl,R (2394)-Schenk,A (2511) Austria 2011 (½-½, 40)} 17.
a3 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 c5 19. Bd6 cxd4 20. Qxd4 Nb6 21. a4 $36) 17. a4 Bb4 18. a5
Nbd7 19. Nxc4 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxe4 (20... Nd5 21. Qd2) 21. Qc2 Bxc4 (21... Nef6
22. Nd6 Bxf1 23. Nxc8 Ba6 24. Nxa7) 22. Bxc4 Ndf6 23. Ba6 $16) (12... dxc4 13.
bxc4 Bxc4 14. Nd2 Ba6 15. Bxc6 Rc8 16. Qa4 $14) 13. Bc1 Nhf6 (13... f5 14. Bb2
Bd6 15. e3 Nhf6 16. Ne2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge2f4] /\Nf4, Ne5.}) 14. Qd3 {White has
consolidated his centre and is ready to break with e2-e4.} (14. Nd2 c5 $1)
14... c5 (14... Rc8 15. e4 c5 16. exd5 exd5 17. Bb2 dxc4 18. bxc4 cxd4 19. Nb5
Nc5 20. Qxd4 $14) 15. Bb2 Rc8 16. Nb5 Bxb5 (16... dxc4 17. bxc4 Bxb5 18. cxb5
c4 19. Qc2 c3 20. Bc1 Qc7 21. e4 Qc4 22. a4 h6 23. Bf4 Rcd8 24. Bf1 Qc8 25. Bd3
$16 {Marin-NN corr 2014}) 17. cxb5 {Due to the permanent threat of an invasion
on c6 and the bishops' pair White is comfortably better.} Ne4 (17... Qc7 18.
Rac1 Qb8 19. e3 $14) 18. Ne5 Nxe5 (18... Ndf6 19. Rac1 cxd4 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21.
Nc6 Qb7 {Marin,M (2539)-Patrascu,C (2275) Calimanesti Caciulata 2017 (½-½,
35)} 22. a4 $16) 19. dxe5 f5 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Bxe4 Bxb2 22. Bxh7+ Kh8 23. Rab1
Qf6 24. Rf1 $14 {Gleizerov,E (2515)-Barua,D (2535) Kolkata 1999 (1-0, 40)} *

