1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 b6 10. b3 a5 $5 {Quite an ambitious move. We are familiar with
the fact that in certain lines the a7-pawn is vulnerable, so Black
over-defends it keeping a choice with respect to the bishop's development. The
obvious drawback is that this does not contribute to the development.} 11. Bc3
Ba6 ({The alternative is, as always,} 11... Bb7 12. Nbd2 Qc7 (12... c5 13. Ne5
cxd4 14. Bxd4 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 $14 {1-0, 56)}) 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 {White
maintains the initiative but according to the player with black he had
analyzed the forced line until the end in Postny, E (2620)-Roiz, M (2608)
Tiberias 2016 (0-1, 57)}) (11... Ne4 {slightly neglects development:} 12. Ne5
Nxe5 13. Bxe4 f5 {Ding,L (2773)-Giri,A (2785) Moscow 2017 CBM 179 [Silver,A] 
(½-½, 28)} 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. dxe5 Bb7 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Bd4 $14) 12. Nbd2 b5
{The thematic way of increasing the bishop's activity.} (12... Rc8 {is more
passive, allowing White open the center to his favour.} 13. e4 c5 14. exd5 exd5
15. Qf5 $5 (15. Qb2 $6 {This leaves the bishop immobile. There are a few
better alternatives, all of them offering White the more pleasant play.} Re8
16. Ne5 {Antic,D (2445)-Solomunovic,I (2402) Novi Banovci 2017 (1-0, 38)} Nxe5
17. dxe5 d4 $13) (15. Ne5 $5) 15... g6 16. Qf4) 13. e4 {This was the only move
I considered.} ({The thematic} 13. c5 $6 {does not work due to} b4 {winning a
pawn.}) 13... bxc4 {The move order is important as it can offer either side
additional possibilities.} (13... dxe4 $6 14. Ne5 Bb7 (14... bxc4 15. Nxc6 cxb3
16. Qxb3 Qe8 17. Bxa5 $16) 15. Nxe4 b4 16. Bd2 Qc8 17. Bg5 $16 {Bernasek,J 
(2395)-Kunte,A (2532) Olomouc 2004 (½-½, 40)}) (13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15.
Qxe4 {[%cal Gc4c5]} bxc4 (15... Rc8 16. c5 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rg8]}) 16. Qxc6 cxb3
17. Ne5 $36) 14. bxc4 ({To tell the truth I did not consider} 14. e5 cxb3 15.
axb3 Ng4 16. Bxa5 Qc8 17. b4 $14 {But I prefer the game continuation anyway as
it offers White lasting initiative.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne5 {
Even though I basically worked out this line over the board, I could not avoid
the feeling that all this was familiar to me.} Nxe5 (16... f5 17. Nxc6 Qe8 18.
Bxa5 Nf6 19. d5 $16 {Ding,L (2742)-Gajewski,G (2659) Tromsoe 2014 (1-0, 40)})
17. dxe5 $14 {White will retrieve the pawn retaining space advantage and more
active bishops.} Qb6 $146 ({Later I discovered that my deja vu feeling was
caused by the following old game:} 17... Qc7 18. Qxe4 Rac8 19. h4 Rfd8 20. h5
h6 21. Bf1 $14 Bb7 $2 (21... Bc5 $14 22. Bd3 $6 f5 23. exf6 Qxg3+) 22. Bd3 Rxd3
23. Qxd3 $16 {Beliavsky,A (2690)-Jussupow,A (2630) Frankfurt 1998 (1-0, 41)
The long-term memory seems to have worked better than the short term one. As
for my opponent I suspect he did not see the old game at all.}) 18. Qxe4 (18.
Bxe4 {can lead to interesting play but the game move is a better way to keep
the pressure. I rejected this line because of} Bxc4 {[%cal Gc4d5] and it seems
that Black can hold his own, indeed.} (18... h6 $6 19. Rd7 Rfe8 (19... Ra7 20.
Bxa5 $1) 20. Bd4 Qb4 21. c5 Rad8 22. a3 Qb5 23. Rd6 Bxd6 24. exd6 $16) 19. Rd7
Ra7 20. Bd4 c5 21. Rxe7 Rxe7 22. Be3 Bd5 (22... Ba6 23. Bxc5 $16) 23. Bxh7+ (
23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Bxc5 Qc6 $19) 23... Kh8 24. Bxc5 Qb7 25. Bxe7 Rc8 26. Bc5 Bh1
27. f3 Qxf3 $132) 18... Rac8 $6 {This does not fight against White's growing
initiative in any way.} (18... Rab8 {is more to the point.} 19. Rab1 Qc7 20. h4
$14) 19. Rab1 Qa7 ({I was secretly hoping for} 19... Qc5 20. Bd4 Qa3 (20...
Qxc4 21. Bf1 $18) 21. Qc2 $16 {when the threat Rd3 wins material. If} Rb8 22.
Bb6 $18) 20. Rd2 (20. Bxa5 Bxc4 $11) 20... g6 {During the game I was not sure
what this move was supposed to mean. But later I realized that Black is so
passive that he hardly has useful moves. It would be not completely
exaggerated saying he is in some sort of Zugzwang.} (20... Rfd8 21. Bxa5 $16) (
20... Rb8 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 22. Qxc6 Bc5 (22... Rb1+ 23. Bf1 $16) 23. h4 Bxc4 24.
Qa4 $16 {[%csl Ga5]}) (20... c5 21. Rdb2 Rb8 22. Qc6 $16) 21. h4 (21. Bxa5 Bxc4
22. Bb6 Qa6 23. a4 Bd5 24. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5]}) 21... Qc5 $6 (21... a4 22.
Bd4 c5 (22... Bc5 23. Bxc5 Qxc5 24. h5 $16 Qxc4 25. Qf3 $18) 23. Be3 $16) 22.
Bf1 $6 ({Over the past few moves I had been considering several other black
moves and it seems that in the meanwhile I forgot about the familiar maneuver:
} 22. Bd4 Qa3 23. Qc2 {I cannot remember the exact thinking process in this
moment, but it could be that I was concerned about my rooks not being
connected. Still, after} Rb8 24. Bb6 $18 {there is no difference with respect
to the previous similar line.}) 22... Rfd8 23. Rbd1 (23. Bd4 {is less
effective now:} Qa3 24. Qc2 Qf3 25. Rb3 Qf5 $14) 23... Rxd2 24. Rxd2 Qa3 (24...
Qa7 25. Rd6 $5 $16 Bxd6 26. exd6 Qc5 27. Qf4 f5 28. d7 Rd8 29. Qc7 Qe7 30. Qxc6
$18) 25. Rd7 $16 {Even after missing the favorable moment to win material
White enjoys a large advantage. Marin, M (2529)-Glud, J (2521) Erice 2017 
(½-½ , 56)} *

