1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 {
The normal closed systems, with the white bishop on c1 still, are slightly
better for him than the ...Bb4+ and ...Be7 lines. Those using English or Reti
move order to reach the Catalan are surely interested in the following lines,
as Black cannot play ...Bb4 with a check.} 8. Rd1 b6 (8... Ne4 {is less
effective since there is no bishop to take on d2.} 9. Nc3 f5 10. b3 b6 11. e3
Bb7 12. Bb2 Bd6 13. Ne2 Qe7 14. Nf4 $14 {with a familiar regrouping.}) 9. b3
Bb7 (9... Ba6 {is examined in line 13.}) 10. Nc3 Rc8 (10... c5 {offers White
the initiative:} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 (11... exd5 12. Bb2 $14 {leads to a Queen's
Indian tabiya with an extra tempo for White.}) 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 ({The same
comment applies to} 12... exd5 13. Bb2 $14) 13. e4 Bb7 14. Bb2 cxd4 ({Black
cannot keep the tension for too long as after completing the development White
already threatens d4-d5:} 14... Rc8 15. d5 exd5 16. exd5 Bf6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18.
Ne5 $14) 15. Nxd4 Rc8 16. Qe2 Qe8 (16... a6 17. Bh3 Rc7 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Bxe6+
Kh8 20. Bxd7 Bc5 (20... Rxd7 21. Qg4 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 $18) 21. Bf5 $16) 17. Nb5
$14) 11. e4 dxe4 (11... c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 $1 {leads to a familiar
situation where the central tension favours White:} dxc4 (13... Qc7 14. Nh4
dxc4 (14... g6 15. cxd5 $16) 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. Nf5 Rfe8 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Nfd6
$18) (13... Re8 14. Nh4 $36) (13... Ba8 14. Qf5 g6 15. Qf4 dxc4 16. d5 $16) 14.
d5 $16 cxb3 $6 15. axb3 {White retrieves the pawn due to the siultaneous
threats d5-d6 and Rxa7. All these lines have been played in several games
confirming White's advantage.}) ({Black has to react somehow as passive
defence does not offer easy life:} 11... h6 12. e5 Ne8 13. h4 Nc7 14. Bf4 Re8
15. Nh2 Bf8 16. Ng4 Qe7 17. Qe2 Red8 18. Rac1 c5 19. dxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxh6 $1 Ne8
(20... gxh6 21. Nf6+ Kh8 22. Qc2 Ne4 23. Ncxe4 dxe4 24. Bxe4 $18 Ne8 25. Bxb7
Nxf6 26. Bxc8) 21. Bg5 f6 22. Be3 $18 {Marin,M (2520)-Adianto,U (2520) Moscow
1994 (½-½, 54)}) 12. Nxe4 c5 (12... Nxe4 13. Qxe4 {consolidates White's
space advantage.} Nf6 (13... Qc7 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. c5 Qe7 17. b4
$16) 14. Qc2 Qc7 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. c5 $16) 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 ({
With the bishop on c1} 13... Nxf6 {simply loses a pawn to} 14. dxc5) 14. Ng5 $1
{A favourable exchange operation, maintaining White's initiative.} Bxg5 15.
Bxb7 Rc7 16. dxc5 Bxc1 (16... Bf6 17. c6 $5 Bxa1 18. Ba3 Qf6 19. Bd6 Rxb7 20.
cxb7 $16 {Iskusnyh,S (2461)-Vokarev,S (2448) Nizhny Tagil 2016 (1-0, 36)}) 17.
Raxc1 Rxb7 (17... bxc5 18. Bg2 Qe7 19. Rd2 Nf6 20. Rcd1 g6 21. Qc3 h5 22. h3
Rfc8 23. f4 $14 {Cvitan,O (2570)-Borgo,G (2370) Porto San Giorgio 1997 (½-½,
39) White's control over the only open file is not easy to neutralize while
the black queenside pawns are weak.}) 18. c6 Rc7 19. Rxd7 Rxd7 20. cxd7 Qxd7
21. Rd1 Qe7 22. Qd3 g6 23. Qd6 Re8 24. Qd7 Kf8 25. Qa4 a5 26. Rd7 Qc5 27. Qb5
Qxb5 28. cxb5 $14 {/+/- Jussupow,A (2555)-Beitar,H (2255) Thessaloniki 1988 
(1-0, 32) The endgame is very unpleasant for Black. He should keep his rook
passive on b8 when White could bring his king to c4 and play a2-a4 and b3-b4.
The kingside counterplay is not effective as after placing the rook on c6
White would restrict the enemy king. In the game, Black abandoned the b6-pawn
but did not get enough counterplay.} *

