b6 9. b3 Ba6 {The more active alternative to 9...Bb7.} 10. Nbd2 ({This is the
standard reply, but if we compare with line 10 above} 10. Bb2 Rc8 11. Nc3 {
also makes sense.}) 10... Rc8 ({At some point} 10... c5 {enjoyed some
popularity, without being really refuted yet.} 11. e4 dxc4 ({The only
reasonable way of avoiding a transposition to the main line with} 11... Rc8)
12. e5 Nd5 13. bxc4 Nb4 {Black has some counterplay but it can be felt that he
is not perfectly coordinated.} 14. Qa4 $5 $146 Bb7 (14... Qc8 15. Ba3 $14) 15.
a3 Nd3 16. d5 $1 {The only way to fight for the initiative.} exd5 (16... N3xe5
17. d6 Bf6 18. Nxe5 Bxg2 19. Nxd7 Bxa1 20. Kxg2 $18) (16... Rb8 $5 {defends
the bishop creating chances for counterplay.} 17. d6 Bg5 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Qxd7
Qxe5 20. Ra2 Nxf2 21. Rf1 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Nd3 23. Qc6 Qe2+ 24. Kg1 Qe3+ 25. Kh1
$14 {WHite keeps the extra piece and chances to convert it.}) 17. cxd5 Bxd5 18.
Nc4 Nxc1 19. Raxc1 Be6 20. Ne1 b5 (20... Qc7 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Nd3 $14) 21.
Qxb5 Rb8 22. Qc6 $14 {/\Nd3-f4 With a pleasant blockade on c4 and a dangerous
kingside majority.}) 11. e4 c5 {The standard reaction.} ({If} 11... Bb7 12. Bb2
({It is better to wait with} 12. e5 {until Black makes some commitment. Under
the given circumstances he can regroup with} Ne8 13. Bb2 Nc7 14. Nf1 c5 $132)
12... Qc7 13. e5 {Now that the c7-square is not available anymore White can
safely advance his pawn.} Ne8 14. Rac1 Qb8 15. b4 Bxb4 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Qa4
Bxd2 18. Nxd2 Rd8 (18... b5 19. Qxb5 Nb6 20. Ba3 Nc7 21. Qa5 $16) 19. Ba3 $18 {
Benkovic,P (2456)-Huss,A (2330) Graechen 2009 (1-0, 36)}) (11... Qc7 12. e5 Ne8
13. Nf1 {/\Bg5, Ng5.} h6 14. Ne3 Bb7 15. Bb2 Qb8 16. Qe2 Nc7 17. Ne1 $16 {
Followed by Nd3-f4 or simply f4-f5 and black is not in time with the freeing
c6-c5.}) 12. exd5 exd5 {If compared to similar tabyias above the knight stands
a bit in the way on d2.} 13. Nf1 $5 {Probably the most accurate move order.
The knight's regrouping is essential anyway while the bishop is active on c1
already.} ({But} 13. Bb2 {loks OK, too.} cxd4 (13... Re8 14. Nf1 {more or less
transposes to the main line.}) 14. Nxd4 b5 15. Nf5 $5 ({I had the occasion to
convince myself that the traditional method} 15. Qf5 {is not too effective:}
bxc4 16. bxc4 g6 17. Qg5 dxc4 18. Nc6 Rxc6 19. Bxc6 Qb6 $44 {Marin,M (2532)
-Berescu, A (2386) Iasi 1999 (1-0, 32) The c4-pawn is very strong and Black
has successfully completed his development.}) 15... bxc4 16. bxc4 Re8 (16...
Bxc4 17. Nxc4 dxc4 18. Bc3 {Gregory,K (2047)-Gray,M (2074) England 2012 (½-½,
36)} Re8 {The only reasonable move.} 19. Rab1 {White's domination is decisive
as the d7-knight is pinned and the black queen has no good squares.} Rc7 20.
Ba5 $18) 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Nxg7 Bf6 (18... Rf8 19. Nf5 $18 Qb6 20. cxd5 Rxc2 $6
21. Nxe7#) 19. Nxe8 Qxe8 20. Re1 Qf8 21. Rad1 $14 {Material is about equal and
White maintains some threats against the enemy king.}) 13... cxd4 {Aiming to
increase the pressure on c4.} (13... dxc4 14. d5 $1 Ne8 (14... cxb3 15. axb3
Bxf1 16. Bxf1 Qc7 17. Bb5 Bd6 18. Bb2 a5 19. Nh4 $16) 15. bxc4 Nd6 16. Ne3 Bf6
17. Rb1 $14) ({The insertion of neutral moves tends favouring White:} 13... Re8
14. Bb2 dxc4 (14... b5 {Mikhalevski,A (2428)-Zoler,D (2464) Israel 2010 (½-½,
27)} 15. cxd5 Bb7 16. Ne5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Qd3 c4 19. bxc4 bxc4 20. Nxc4
$14) (14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 dxc4 16. Ne3 cxb3 17. Qb1 $1 b5 18. Nc6 Qb6 19. Nxe7+
Rxe7 20. axb3 $16 {Menezes,C (2408)-Rajdeep,S (2351) Bhubaneswar 2016 (1-0, 35)
