1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 {We now start investigating the lines
in which Black takes the c4-pawn on the first given occasion, aiming to either
keep it or start counterplay in the center. Play frequently takes a forced
course.} 5. Bg2 c5 {One of the most important lines. By completely clearing
the center Black hopes equalizing gradually in what remains basically a
pleasant position for White.} 6. O-O Nc6 7. dxc5 $5 {Possibly the simplest 
(but not at all simplistic!) ways of keeping an edge, even though sometimes
quite a small one.} ({The traditional main lines are} 7. Ne5) ({and} 7. Qa4)
7... Qxd1 (7... Bxc5 {allows WHite somewhat spoiling Black's coordination:} 8.
Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nd2 Bb5 (10... c3 {Atalik,S (2455)-Smagin,S (2550)
Yugoslavia 1992 (½-½, 29)} 11. bxc3 $14 {with relatively similar play as in
the main line.}) 11. a4 Ba6 12. Ndxc4 Nd7 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 {Lampert,J (2469)
-Janssen,R (2479) Germany 2016 (½-½, 67)} 14. Ne5+ Ke7 15. Rb1 {The threat
b4-b5 forces Black wasting more time with his bihop.} Bb4 (15... Bd4 16. b4
Bxe2 17. Re1 Bxe5 18. Rxe2 Bd4 19. Rc2 e5 20. Ba3 Kd7 21. Rbc1 $14) (15... Bxe2
16. Re1 Bh5 17. b4 Bd4 18. Ba3 $36) 16. Rd1 f6 17. Rd4 Bc5 18. Rd7+ Ke8 19. Nd3
$1 {White wins an essential tempo for if} Kxd7 20. Nxc5+ Ke7 21. Nxa6 $18) 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 {As e will see, the positional damage provoked by this
move is minimal.} ({The extravagant} 9... Ng4 {misplacing the knight, deserves
being mentioned as White needs readjusting his plans.} 10. Ne4 (10. e3 Bxe3 {
is not entirely clear.}) 10... Be7 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Rxd6 {The weakness of the
dark squares at least compensates for the missing pawn.} Ke7 (12... e5 {
Dyachkov,S (2510)-Serper,G (2575) Moscow 1994 (½-½, 47)} 13. b3 cxb3 14. axb3
O-O 15. h3 Nf6 16. Bb2 {also offers White ample compensation for the pawn.})
13. Rd1 Rd8 (13... e5 14. b3 Rd8 15. Ba3+ Ke8 16. Rxd8+ Kxd8 17. Rd1+ Ke8 {
Kurajica, B (2527)-Saraci, N (1872) Kukes 2013 (1-0, 30) White's compensation
is obvious and the most convincing way of keeping the initiative is} 18. Nd2 $1
$146 cxb3 19. axb3 Nd4 20. Nc4 Nxe2+ 21. Kf1 Nd4 22. Nd6+ Kd7 23. Nxf7 Ke6 24.
Nxe5 Kxe5 25. Bb2 $16) 14. Rxd8 Kxd8 15. Bd2 e5 16. Rc1 $14 {Miles,A (2580)
-Seirawan, Y (2585) USA 1989 (½-½, 53) White retrieves the pawn with very
pleasant play.}) (9... O-O 10. Nxc4 {is simply good for White, who has the
much better development in a symmetrical but open position.}) (9... Na5 10. Ne5
{is similar and} c3 $6 {does not restrict White's initiative.} 11. bxc3 Nd7 12.
Nec4 Nxc4 13. Nxc4 f6 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. Rxd6 Nb6 16. Rd4 Rb8 {Davies,N (2475)
-Chernin,A (2560) Moscow 1988 (½-½, 40)} 17. a4 $16) 10. bxc3 {White may
well use the b-file and his isolated c-pawn will be part of the central
initiative. Sometimes even a2-a4-a5 is an issue.} O-O (10... e5 11. Nc4 Ne4 (
11... Ng4 12. Nd6+ $14 Kf8 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Nd6 $16) (11... e4 12. Nd4 $16) 12.
Nfxe5 $1 $146 {Not fearing ghosts.} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Nxf2 14. Rd5 $1 {It appears
that Black's pieces are hanging.} Bb6 15. Nc4 Ng4+ 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. Rb5 $16)
11. Nb3 {When I started playing the Catalan, I tried making this plan work,
but somehow did not believe in White's dynamic resources in the absence of the
queens. It seems I was wrong.} Be7 (11... Bb6 {leaves the a3-f8 diagonal to
White's mercy.} 12. Ba3 Rd8 (12... Re8 13. Nfd2 e5 14. Nc4 Bc7 15. Nc5 e4 {
Huzman,A (2602)-Robson,R (2455) Moscow 2009 (1-0, 67)} 16. Rab1 $14) 13. Rxd8+
Bxd8 14. Nfd4 (14. Rd1 Bb6 15. c4 Bd7 16. Nfd2 Rd8 17. c5 Bc7 18. Nc4 $14)
14... Ne5 {Pein,M (2420)-Smagin,S (2520) London 1990 (1-0, 32)} 15. Nd2 Ba5 16.
Bb4 Bxb4 17. cxb4 $14 {Once again Black has problems completing his
development.}) 12. c4 Bd7 {The traditional method.} ({The more active} 12... e5
{is not without drawbacks as it weakens Black's centre.} 13. Bb2 e4 (13... Nd7
14. Nfd2 f6 {Buhmann,R (2572)-Herbold,M (2170) Leinzell 2011 (1-0, 34)} 15. a4
Ndb8 16. Ba3 Bxa3 17. Rxa3 Na6 18. Bd5+ Kh8 19. Ne4 Rd8 20. a5 $14 {with
unpleasant white pressure involving all his pieces and ueenside pawns.}) 14.
Nfd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. Nb5 Bc6 17. Rab1 Nd7 {Mikaelyan,A (2445)-Chigladze,
I (2364) Tbilisi 2015 (½-½, 67)} 18. Nc7 Rac8 19. Nd5 $14) 13. Bb2 Rfd8 14.
Nfd4 Rac8 (14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bc6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 {1-0 (48) Sasikiran,K (2637)
-Pichot,A (2542) Moscow 2016} 17. Na5 c5 18. Be3 $14) 15. Nb5 b6 {As we will
see Black will not be able to block on c5. But at least he gets the b-pawn out
of the bishop's range.} ({I faced the more passive but also solid} 15... Be8 {
in a blitz game:} 16. c5 {White has no reason for refraining from the main
plan. The invasion on d6 is very unpleasant for Black.} Rxd1+ ({It makes sense
exchanging a rook as Black has little space.} 16... Nd5 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. cxd6
Nb8 19. Rac1 Ba4 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Rc7 $16 {So,W (2760)-Kaidanov,G (2561) Las
Vegas 2015 (1-0, 46)}) 17. Rxd1 Kf8 (17... Nd8 18. Nd6 Bxd6 19. cxd6 Ba4 20.
Rd2 $16 {Caruana,F (2711)-Svidler,P (2739) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011 (0-1, 37)}) 18.
Nd6 {White is better.} Rc7 {Marin,M (2545)-Jianu,V (2582) Medias (blitz) 2016 
(½-½, 37)} 19. Bc3 $14) 16. Nd6 $1 {Not only spoiling Black's coordination 
(or else gaining the two bishops) but also enabling the planed c4-c5.} Rc7 {
The most natural answer. Black keeps his rook on the open file, refraining
from making any positional concessions yet.} (16... Rb8 17. Rd2 $14) ({A
player with good defensive skills and good capacity of endurance would consider
} 16... Bxd6 17. Rxd6 Be8 18. Rxd8 Nxd8 19. Rc1 $14 Bc6 (19... Nd7 20. f4 Nc5
21. Nxc5 Rxc5 22. Ba3 Rc8 23. c5 b5 24. Rd1 $14) 20. f3 $1 {Keeping the two
bishops.} Nd7 21. c5 $1 (21. Ba3 Nb7 {[%csl Gc5] followed by a blockade on c5.}
) 21... Bd5 22. cxb6 Rxc1+ 23. Nxc1 Nxb6 24. e4 Bc4 25. Kf2 $14 {The bishop
pair and the more active king offer White the better ending. How big his
winning chances are - that is another question. But from a practical point of
view it surely is no fun to play with Back.}) 17. Ba3 $1 {A key move in
White's plan. The bishop was not doing much on the long diagonal, while from
a3 it creates all sorts of tactical motifs. The immediate threat is 18.Nb5
Rcc8 19.Bxc6 winning a piece.} Kf8 {Since White's coordination is obviously
better, Ponomariov tries to relieve his position by using numeric superiority.
This is a known method when the game gets close to an ending. If the defending
side can use his king as an extra piece in the main area of combat, he has
every chance of a favorable outcome. The main problem is that the position is
far from getting to an endgame yet, being closer to a complex queenless
middlegame. This makes the last move double-edged.} ({Тhere was no obvious
way to equalize. If} 17... Ne5 18. Nb5 Bxb5 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. cxb5 {Тhe
strong Catalan bishop and the queenside space advantage offers White better
chances in the endgame. A possible continuation is' the strong Catalan bishop
and the queenside space advantage offers White better chances in the endgame.
A possible continuation is} Be7 21. Bxe7 (21. Rc1 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 $14) 21...
Rxe7 22. Rc1 g5 23. Nd4 Rd7 24. Rc8+ Kg7 25. e3 {Black is solid but awfully
passive. White may well fail to prove a way to increase his advantage, but who
would like to sit and wait with Black for the rest of the endgame?'} Nd5 26.
Bxd5 Rxd5 27. Rc7 {1/2-1/2 (66) Lei,T (2455)-Zhang,X (2364) Wuxi 2015}) ({
We can also understand that Black was not keen to weaken his queenside with} 
17... a6 18. c5 bxc5 (18... b5 19. Bb2 $14) 19. Rac1 Ne5 20. Nxc5 Bc8 21. Nxc8
Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rxc8 23. Rc1 a5 24. Nb3 Rxc1+ 25. Bxc1 $14 {Another version of
the ending with the bishop pair. Additionally, the a5-pawn is vulnerable.}) 18.
c5 {Reinforcing the threat 19.Nb5, this time with a different idea (see the
next comment to better understand).} Nb8 $2 {The decisive mistake.} ({A
neutral move such as} 18... h6 {would run into} 19. Nb5 Rcc8 20. Bxc6 Rxc6 21.
Nxa7 Rc7 22. cxb6 {In this line, the Catalan bishop proved its force by a
well-timed capture on c6. With his last move, Ponomariov not only cleared the
long diagonal but took the b5-square under control as well. In doing so, he
failed to notice the hidden force of the other bishop.}) ({A better way of
neutralizing the g2-bishop would have been} 18... Nd5 {In some lines White may
win a pawn, but his pieces could be left a bit hanging.} 19. Rac1 bxc5 20. Bxd5
exd5 21. Bxc5 Be6 22. Nb5 Rb7 23. N5d4 $14 {White will soon reach an ending
with a good knight against a (at least theoretically) bad bishop.}) 19. Nb5 $1
{Unexpectedly, this move is possible and winning! Ponomariov sank into deep
thought (possibly interrupted by self-reproaches) for almost half an hour, but
there is nothing to be saved anymore.} Rcc8 ({The tactical point is that} 19...
Bxb5 {loses the exchange to} 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 21. cxb6+) 20. Nxa7 Rc7 21. cxb6 {
White has won two pawns retaining a normal coordination. The game is over.
Cheparinov,I (2681)-Ponomariov,R (2717) Tromsoe 2014 (1-0, 37)} *

