1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 {This interesting move,
deviating a bit from the standard way of development (knights first and only
then bishops) has been fashionable in several historical moments, each time
for different reasons.} 6. Ne5 {The most principled move, gaining the bishops'
pair.} (6. O-O Bc6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Qxc4 {would offer White a stable advantage
if he would be in time playing Nc3, with similar play as after 7...Bd7 in line
5. But Black has} Bd5 9. Qd3 Be4 10. Qd1 c5 11. Nc3 Bc6 {followed by ...cxd4
with a rather symbolic white initiative. The recent try} 12. e4 $5 {looks
principled but does not yield an advantage if Black defends accurately.} Nxe4
13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Re1 Bd5 15. dxc5 Be7 16. b4 O-O 17. Bb2 a5 18. a3 {In Czebe,
A (2466)-Lalith, B (2553) New Delhi 2016 (1-0, 31) White's queenside space
advantage eventually prevailed but after theaccurate} axb4 19. axb4 b6 $1 {
play simplifies to a draw after, say,} 20. Ne5 Rxa1 21. Bxa1 Nxe5 22. Bxd5 exd5
23. Rxe5 bxc5 $11) 6... Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. e3 Qd7 9. O-O Rd8 $5 {This trendy
move increases the pressure in the center and removes the rook from the
g2-bishop's range without exposing the king as in the line which used to be
fashionable until recently (see 9...0-0-0 below.} ({The old line went} 9... Rb8
10. Qe2 b5 11. b3 cxb3 12. axb3 Rb6 13. Rd1 {Playing for the pawn break with
d4-d5.} ({Actually even the simplistic} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Rxa7 $14 {is
preferable for White due to his better structure.}) 13... a6 14. Nc3 Be7 15.
Bb2 Nb4 16. e4 O-O 17. Bh3 Qe8 18. Na2 Nd7 19. Bc3 Nxa2 20. Rxa2 c5 21. d5 exd5
22. exd5 $14 {With strong initiative due to the strong bishops and passed pawn,
Petursson, M (2560)-Polgar, S (2415) Aarhus 1993 (1-0, 36) This was one of the
games that temporarily caused 5...Bd7 stepping out of the limelight.}) ({
The attempt to carry out the plan after 9...0-0-0 but without exposing the
king yet with} 9... Nd5 {is best answered with} 10. Nd2 h5 (10... c3 11. bxc3
Nxc3 12. Qc2 Nd5 13. Rb1 Rb8 14. Nb3 $36) 11. Nxc4 h4 {Cheparinov,I (2665)
-Grachev,B (2660) Moscow 2011 (1-0, 57)} 12. b4 $5 {Speeding up the queenside
play.} (12. Bd2 $5 {/\b4}) 12... hxg3 13. hxg3 Bxb4 14. a3 Be7 15. Qb3 {
and White's threats are more concrete than Black's.}) ({The line starting with
} 9... O-O-O $5 {was recommended some years ago by Jeroen Bosch in one of his
SOS articles for New in Chess.} 10. Nc3 $5 {This is not too popular yet, but
to me, it looks like the most principled reaction. Black develops the knight
on the most active square without bothering to retrieve the pawn. White's main
idea is opening the queenside with b2-b3. His play is developing fast and with
natural moves.} ({If White plays naturally,} 10. Qe2 {the plan advocated by
Bosch is} h5 11. Qxc4 Nd5 12. Nc3 h4 13. Bd2 f5 14. Rfc1 hxg3 15. hxg3 g5 {
with very dangerous initiative.}) (10. Nd2 {is a correct idea in principle,
but Black gets counterplay with} e5 $5 {A series of best black moves leads to
approximate equality.} 11. Nxc4 exd4 12. exd4 Qe6 13. Qa4 Rxd4 14. b3 Ne4 15.
Bb2 Nc5 16. Qxc6 bxc6 17. Bxd4 Ne4 {White has excellent compensation for the
queen, but apparently not an advantage. A typical Giri game went} 18. Rae1 f5
19. f3 Qd5 20. fxe4 Qxd4+ 21. Kh1 Bb4 22. Rd1 Qc3 23. Rc1 Qd4 24. Rcd1 Qc3 25.
Rc1 Qd4 26. Rcd1 {1/2-1/2 Giri,A-Harikrishna,P/Biel 2014/CBM 162 (26)}) 10...
Nd5 (10... h5 11. b3 Bb4 {Gelfand,B (2734)-Harika,D (2514) Almaty (blitz) 2016
(1-0, 47)} 12. Ne2 $5) (10... e5 11. Qa4 Kb8 12. Qxc4 exd4 13. exd4 Qxd4 14.
Qxf7 $14 {Ju,W (2547)-Venkatesh,M (2460) Caleta 2015 (1-0, 33)}) 11. Bd2 Bb4 (
11... h5 12. b3 $36) 12. Qe2 Nb6 13. Rfd1 f5 14. b3 cxb3 15. axb3 Kb8 16. Na4
Nd5 17. Rdc1 Bd6 18. b4 h5 19. b5 Nce7 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 $18 {Sasikiran,K 
(2639)-Ponomariov,R (2710) Berlin 2015 (1-0, 73)}) 10. Qe2 e5 ({Obviously the
only answer as} 10... b5 11. a4 a6 12. axb5 axb5 13. b3 {leads to queenside
disaster.}) 11. Nc3 {Now that the center is likely to open, the knight should
take the e4- and d5-squares under control.} ({I would also mention an untested
yet idea:} 11. Nd2 exd4 12. exd4+ Be7 13. Nf3 {for the case some significant
improvement is found for Black in the main line. White's plan is retrieving
the pawn and keeping some light pressure along the long diagonal, even though
Black enjoys certain stability.} Qd5 (13... O-O 14. Qxc4 Qd5 15. Qc2 $14) (
13... Qe6 14. Qxe6 fxe6 15. Re1 O-O 16. Rxe6 Nd5 17. Bd2 Bf6 18. Re4 $14) 14.
Be3 O-O 15. Rad1 $14) 11... Be7 {The most logical move as it is best to defend
the e-file and keep the d-file clear.} (11... Bd6 12. Qxc4 exd4 13. exd4 O-O
14. Rd1 h6 15. Be3 $14 {is an improved version over the same structure,
Shankland,S (2674)-Libiszewski,F (2545) Caleta 2017 (½-½, 40)}) (11... exd4 {
opens the d-file too quickly:} 12. exd4+ Be7 13. d5 Nb4 14. Bg5 $14 {Kraemer,M
(2570)-Luther,T (2541) Austria 2016 (½-½, 42)}) 12. Rd1 $1 exd4 13. Qxc4 O-O
(13... d3 14. Qb5 Qc8 15. Rxd3 O-O {White has two bishops and a mobile
queenside majority. He only needs getting coordinated and developed. The best
way of achieving it is} 16. Bd2 $5 $14) 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. Qxc6 bxc6 16. Rxd4
Rxd4 17. exd4 Nd5 18. Bd2 {This ending is not that simple for Black as it may
seem. His double pawns are a permanent source of worries.} Nxc3 19. Bxc3 Bd6
20. Ba5 Rb8 21. b4 Rb5 (21... Kf8 22. Rc1 Ke8 23. Rxc6 Kd7 $14) 22. a3 Kf8 23.
Rc1 Ke8 24. Rxc6 $16 Kd7 25. Ra6 Kc8 26. a4 Rd5 27. b5 Rxd4 28. Bc3 $16 {
Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2652)-Moskalenko,A (2488) Moscow 2017 (1-0, 37)} *

