1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. O-O a6 7. e3 Bd7 {
Black plans a different development than in the game, but White can play
exactly the same with similar results.} ({With respect to 8...Bd6 below,} 7...
Bd6 $2 {is premature due to} 8. Nbd2 $16 {/\Nxc4 since} b5 $2 9. Ne5 $18 {
loses material.}) (7... Rb8 {is a somewhat mysterious move but has some hidden
ideas. It has been played a few times by a player who likes taking risks at an
early stage, Mamedyarov (but mainly in blitz games). The main question is
whether after} 8. Nfd2 {, when ...b7-b5 is not possible, the rook move is not
useful at all. The main way to try activating the rook is} e5 (8... Qd7 {
is a more peaceful alternative.} 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Ncd2 Be7 {In this position the
knight usually goes to b3, now or on the next move, but this fails to prevent..
.e6-e5 and also exposes the knight to ...a6-a5. Therefore, it makes sense
trying} 11. Nf3 $5 $146 O-O 12. b3 Rd8 13. Qe2 a5 14. a3 $14 {when Black will
not find it easy carrying out any of the central breaks.}) 9. Bxc6+ {White has
to accept the pawn, as otherwise, his center would vanish. But now the rook
becomes active, partly justifying Black's plan.} bxc6 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Nxc4 Be6
12. Nbd2 h5 (12... Bb4 {may retrieve the pawn but leave Black passive and with
his structure weak:} 13. b3 Bc3 14. Rb1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. f4 Bd6 17. f5
Bc8 18. Bb2 $14) 13. f3 Rb4 14. fxg4 {A practical decision, leading to a
somewhat better ending.} ({Actually it is not clear whether Black's threats
are strong enough to compensate for the piece after} 14. Qe2 h4 15. fxg4 hxg3
16. b3 Rxh2 17. Qf3 Qd5 18. Ne4 {for instance} g2 19. Rf2 Rxc4 20. bxc4 Qxe5
21. Ng3 Qxa1 22. Qxc6+ Kd8 23. Kxh2 Qxc1 24. Kxg2 {The position is far from
one-sided, as the bishops could be dangerous. But White is a clear exchange up
and Black's king is also exposed, so White should be better.}) 14... Bxc4 15.
Nxc4 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Rxc4 17. Bd2 Rxg4 18. Rac1 Rh6 19. Ba5 Be7 (19... h4 {
is premature:} 20. Rd4 Rg5 21. Bxc7 hxg3 22. hxg3 Rxg3+ 23. Kf2 Rgh3 24. Rd8+
Ke7 25. Rb8 {and Black's coordination is poor.}) 20. Bxc7 Rb4 ({Black would
have better chances to equalize after} 20... h4 21. Rd4 Bg5 22. Rxg4 Bxe3+ 23.
Kg2 Bxc1 24. b3 hxg3 25. hxg3) {Matlakov,M (2730)-Naiditsch,A (2702) Heraklio
2017 (1-0, 57) Instead of 21.Rc2, keeping the rook busy with defending b2,
White should have played} 21. b3 $1 $146 Re6 22. Rc4 Rb7 23. Ba5 $16 {when the
c6-pawn is really hanging.}) 8. Qe2 b5 (8... Bd6 {induces a different plan.
Black is heading for opening the center with ...e6-e5. But his bishop will
stand far from optimally on d7 and b7 will be hanging many times, while after
the exchanges in the center White will get a mobile kingside majority.} 9. Qxc4
O-O 10. Nbd2 e5 (10... Qe7 {Leenhouts,K (2499)-Azarov,S (2577) Bastia 2016 
(0-1, 49) does not change White's plans with respect to the main line:} 11. Qc2
e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nc4 $14) (10... Nb4 {leads to artificial
play:} 11. Qe2 Bb5 12. Nc4 a5 13. a3 Nbd5 14. a4 Ba6 15. b3 c6 16. Bb2 $14 {
with stable space advantage for White, Cheparinov,I (2688) -Azarov,S (2582)
Minsk 2017 (1-0, 41)}) (10... Rb8 {defends b7 in advance in order to prepare ..
.e6-e5. But this offers WHite an important tempo which he could use in several
ways. For instance 11.b3 e5 12.Bb2 reaching a position where Black usually has
...Qe7 instead of ...Rb8 and could play ...e5-e4. Or else} 11. Qc2 {clearing
the c4-square for the knight.} Nb4 {The only attempt at counterplay.} 12. Qb3
a5 {Kuzubov,Y (2690)-Szabo,G (2563) Heraklio 2017 (½-½, 31)} 13. a3 a4 14.
Qd1 Nd3 15. Qc2 Bb5 16. Nc4 Nxc1 17. Raxc1 $14 {Even though he faces no
immediate threats, Black is far from freeing his position completely.}) 11.
dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Raznikov,D (2484)-Wagner,D (2572) Zalakaros 2015 (1-0,
61)} 13. Qc5 $5 Bd6 14. Qc2 $14 {The b7-pawn is hanging and the threat Nc4
will gain either time or the bishops' pair. The central majority will soon be
ready for advancing.}) 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 Be7 11. Bd2 $1 ({I prefer this over
} 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Rc1 Nb4 13. Ne5 Rc8 {which has been played in several games.
Black prepares freeing his play with ...c7-c5.}) 11... O-O 12. Rc1 Nd5 (12...
Ra7 {is a somewhat contorted regrouping as Black cannot achieve ...c7-c5
easily.} 13. Nc3 Nb8 14. Ne5 Be8 15. Na2 Nd5 16. Qe1 Bd6 17. Nd3 Qe7 18. e4 Nb6
19. e5 Ba3 20. Rc2 $16 {With very passive play for Black, who also has
numerous weaknesses, Berczes, D (2520)-Goloshchapov, A (2576) Germany 2011 
(1-0, 40)}) 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Ra7 15. Ne1 b4 {Kunte,A (2515)-Sengupta,D 
(2589) Thiruvarur 2015 (½-½, 31)} 16. Bb2 (16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Bxb4 Ba8 {
allows Black regrouping properly with chances for counterplay.}) 16... Nb8 17.
Qg4 $5 $14 {Planning Nd3. Due to the vulnerability of the g7-square Black
cannot even think to play ...c7-c5.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 Open system"]
[Black "5...Nc6 6...Rb8"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E04"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "45"]
[EventDate "2017.12.24"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nc6 {QUite an ambitious system.
Black simply intends keeping the extra pawn with ...Rb8 (or ...a7-a6) and ...
b7-b5.} ({Another possible move order is} 5... a6 6. O-O Nc6) 6. O-O Rb8 7. e3
{The start of a very consistent regrouping. White's main idea is revealed on
the next move.} b5 8. b3 $5 cxb3 9. axb3 {White has the a- and b-files for his
rooks and a wonderful square on c5. Black's knight stands in the way of his
colleagues on c6 and finding a better place is not easy as we will see. His
main plan is Bd2, Qe2, Rc1, Be1, Nbd2, Ne1-d3.} a6 {Black cannot do without
this move for too long, for instance} (9... Bb7 10. Qe2 {attacking b5}) ({or} 
9... Be7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Bd2 Bb7 12. Rc1 {and ...a7-a6 is needed to free the
knight.}) 10. Qe2 Bb7 (10... Be7 11. Bd2 {does not change much.}) 11. Bd2 Ne4 (
11... Nb4 {Kanep,M (2532)-Jumabayev,R (2547) Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (½-½, 14)
offers White chances invading the weak c6-square:} 12. Ne5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Rb6 (
13... Qd5+ 14. Kg1 Qxb3 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Rxa6 O-O 17. Nc6 Rb7 18. e4 $14) 14.
Qf3 Qd5 15. Rc1 Qxf3+ 16. Kxf3 $14) (11... Be7 12. Rc1 O-O (12... Nd5 {exposes
the knight to an undesired exchange:} 13. Nc3 $1 {WHite does not need wasting
time with Be1 to develop this knight.} Ndb4 14. Ne4 {And now the e4-square is
available.} O-O 15. Nc5 Bc8 16. Ne5 $16 {Sasikiran,K (2681)-Topalov,V (2803)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (½-½, 25)}) 13. Ne1 Nb4 (13... Nd5 14. Nd3 Qc8 15. Nc5
Bxc5 16. Rxc5 Rd8 17. Be1 Nce7 18. Nd2 $14 {Marin,M (2545)-Riazantsev,A (2678)
European Individual Blitz Chess Championship, Tallin 2016 (0-1, 34)}) 14. Bxb7
Rxb7 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Rxa6 Bxe1 17. Qxe1 Qd5 {Marin,M (2549)-Cosma,E (2324)
Medias (rapid) 2016 (½-½, 38)} 18. Qd1 $14 {Anticipating Black's plan based
on ...Nd7 and ...e6-e5.} Nd7 $6 19. Nc3 Qf5 20. e4 Qg6 21. Qe2 $16) 12. Rc1 Qc8
(12... Nxd2 {gets the b4-suare for the knight but speeds up White's
development.} 13. Nbxd2 Nb4 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qd5+ 16. e4 Qb7 (16... Qxd4
17. Ndf3 Qa7 18. Ng5 Be7 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Qh5+ $40) {Salgado Lopez,I (2630)
-Libiszewski,F (2481) Aix les Bains 2011 (½-½, 51)} 17. d5 Bd6 18. Nc6 Nxc6
19. Rxc6 $44 {with pleasant domination on light squares.}) 13. Be1 Bd6 14. Nfd2
$1 ({An improvement over} 14. Nh4 f5 $6 (14... Nd8 $1 15. Qg4 f5 16. Qxg7 Nf7
17. Bxe4 Bxe4 {[%cal Gd6f8,Gf8e7]}) 15. Qh5+ Ke7 16. Nd2 Nf6 (16... Nxd2 17.
Bxd2 Nb4 18. Bxb4 Bxb4 19. d5) 17. Qg5 Nd8 18. e4 (18. Qxg7+ Nf7 $19) 18... Nf7
19. Qe3 $40 {Ponomariov,R (2715)-Aleksandrov,A (2592) Gjakova 2016 (1-0, 69)})
14... Nxd2 {The series of exchanges started with this move tends favorite
White.} 15. Nxd2 Nb4 16. Ne4 Bxe4 17. Bxb4 (17. Bxe4 $5 O-O 18. Bc3 Rd8 19. Qd2
Nd5 20. Ba5 $44) 17... Bxg2 (17... Bxb4 18. Bxe4 O-O 19. Rc6 $36 Rb6 (19... a5
20. Rac1 $14 Rb7 $6 21. R6c2 Ra7 22. Qxb5 $16) 20. Qc2 Rxc6 21. Qxc6 a5 22.
Qxb5 $14) 18. Bxd6 Qd7 19. Be5 Bb7 20. Rxc7 Qd5 21. f3 $1 {White once again
sacrifices a pawn in order to stop Black's counterplay.} Qxf3 (21... O-O 22.
Rc5 $18) (21... Rd8 22. e4 $18) 22. Qxf3 Bxf3 23. Bd6 $16 {with huge
initiative with opposite-colored bishops. The study of the open systems will
continue in the second database.} *

